[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring class invocation options**\n\nI‚Äôm trying to figure out the best way to cover `Class.forName`. Should I directly invoke `class$` via reflection? The rules suggest that unless the public API calls for it, reflection shouldn‚Äôt be used. There's this existing test that uses `MethodHandle`, which isn‚Äôt considered direct reflection. I‚Äôm considering whether invoking a private generated method is acceptable, but it‚Äôs not part of the public API. Plus, we need to keep everything outside the library package. I need to decide on using `MethodHandles`.\n\n**Clarifying coverage instrumentation**\n\nI'm trying to understand if the coverage instrumentation tracks calls in a native image instead of during Java tests. I‚Äôm thinking that maybe the test caught an `ObjenesisException` before it reached `class$`, but for `getDeclaredMethod` to work, it had to resolve `ObjectInputStream` and `Class.class` via `class$`. The JAR has synthetic fields, but our reset uses field names with `$`. If the reset fails, the test would likely error, but maybe it wouldn't. This needs some careful thought!\n\n**Evaluating app class access**\n\nI'm considering whether Class.forName is accessible if the app class is reachable. It looks like the existing GCJ passes, so I might need to add a method. I should also read the current file before making any edits and commit those changes. Since previous commits exist, I‚Äôll need to create a new commit, but I won't run tests at this stage. Let's see how this goes!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0e345a3b16969c960169ef7cae715c8195b35e8ae5de518d8f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp73y8EiEleUHbZ0usbSRmBIdD_r5S4GADD20TZzir7gkVzBvSVk1BMJ9wjfiSrHnsIAorCvvYjzmUDSxbZUshwmmlXd3z4AeYutLzal0BkQIqkHYgA-SZQGj_--PQbsRUKprSiyP0pAjSvZ-EnR4cjclBywhbrdzi_aZHSwa6Wr77I6u6IvWSIMqH1WBaby4A7Rcvy3TXf68SqaMSDyOJ30DjGxK0cJEbK4Jd2OqJR